  <title translate="true">Understanding the Motion Graphs</title>
  <keywords>
    <keyword translate="true">Understanding Motion Graphs<keyword translate="true">P, V, A , J</keyword></keyword>
  </keywords>
  <body>
    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1"><text styleclass="Heading1" translate="true">Understanding the Motion Graphs</text></para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="Heading4 Toggle_atocs_"><text styleclass="Heading4 Toggle_atocs_" translate="true">Motion</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Body Text"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">Motion is an abstract concept. It is difficult to order a motion off </text><text styleclass="Body Text" style="font-style:italic;" translate="true">eBay</text><text styleclass="Body Text" style="font-size:7pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super;" translate="true">®</text><text styleclass="Body Text" style="font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:baseline;" translate="true">,</text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true"> for example. </text></para>
    <para styleclass="Body Text"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">For motion design software to be useful, we must represent the motion somehow. The easiest method is to plot a motion as a graph. This is what </text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">MotionDesigner</text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true"> does. Another method to represent the motion is to move machine-elements in a CAD-model with the same motion as the motion graph. This is what </text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">MechDesigner</text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true"> does.</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Heading4 Toggle_atocs_"><text styleclass="Heading4 Toggle_atocs_" translate="true">Motion Graphs in MotionDesigner</text></para>
    <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><table styleclass="AStandard" rowcount="3" colcount="1" style="border-width:0px; border-spacing:0px; cell-border-width:0px; border-style:none;">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="Body Text"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">There are four graphs available in </text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">MotionDesigner</text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">: </text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">Position, Velocity, Acceleration</text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true"> and </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="MT-POP-Jerk" styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">Jerk</link></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">You can use the </text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">P,V,A, J</text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true"> icons in the </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="MT-View-Toolbar" styleclass="SeeAlso" translate="true">View Toolbar</link><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">, to show or hide the motion graph of each motion-derivative.</text></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="Normal"><image src="MT-MotionDesigner-MotionOnlyExample-Understanding.png" scale="100.00%" styleclass="Image Caption" figurelistinclude="0"></image></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="T_Emphasis"><text styleclass="Interface2" translate="true">CONCEPT 1</text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">: We use the same X–axis</text><image src="Red-14-1.gif" scale="100.00%" styleclass="VariableName" figurelistinclude="0"></image><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">  for all the Graphs</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">The </text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">X–axis</text><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true"> is below the motion graphs.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">The </text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">X–axis</text><text styleclass="Body Text" style="font-style:italic;" translate="true"> </text><text styleclass="Body Text" style="font-style:normal;" translate="true">is</text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true"> common to all </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="MT-POP-Motion-Derivative" styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">motion-derivatives</link><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">. </text></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">The graph of each </text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">motion-derivative</text><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true"> (Position, Velocity, Acceleration, and Jerk) are exactly above each other. </text></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">In practice, the motion repeats. Hence, the first-point follows the last point. </text></para>
          <para styleclass="Heading HowTo_atoc_" style="text-align:left; text-indent:0px; margin-top:0px; margin-right:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; line-height:1.00; background-color:transparent; white-space:normal; page-break-inside:auto; page-break-after:auto; border:none; tabstops:none;"><text styleclass="Interface2" translate="true">CONCEPT 2: </text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">It is the same motion for motion-derivatives</text><image src="Red-14-2.gif" scale="100.00%" styleclass="VariableName" figurelistinclude="0"></image><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">All of the graphs above and below each other show the same </text><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">motion, but they show a different</text><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true"> </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="MT-POP-Motion-Derivative" styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">motion-derivative</link><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="T_Emphasis"><text styleclass="Interface2" translate="true">CONCEPT 3: </text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">The Motion is split into Segments </text></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">It is convenient to split the motion into </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="MT-POP-Segment" styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">Segments</link><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">. </text></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">For each Segment, you select a </text><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="MT-POP-Motion-Laws" styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">Motion-Law</link><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true"> that can satisfy the specification for the motion design.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="T_Emphasis"><text styleclass="Interface2" translate="true">concept 4</text><text styleclass="T_Emphasis" translate="true">: </text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">Blend-Points</text><image src="Red-14-4.gif" scale="100.00%" styleclass="VariableName" figurelistinclude="0"></image><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true"> at each end of each Segment</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text" translate="true">We join the Segments end-to-end with Blend-Points.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="T_Emphasis"><text styleclass="Interface2" translate="true">CONCEPT 5: </text><text styleclass="T_Emphasis" translate="true"> </text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">Segment naming conventions.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">For convenience, we name the segments as the:</text></para>
          <list id="0" type="ul" listtype="bullet" formatstring="·" format-charset="SYMBOL_CHARSET" levelreset="true" legalstyle="false" startfrom="1" styleclass="HowTo Bulleted" style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; color:#000000;">
            <li styleclass="HowTo Bulleted"><link displaytype="text" defaultstyle="true" type="topiclink" href="MT-POP-Selected-Segment" styleclass="Element" translate="true">Selected-Segment</link><image src="Red-14-3.gif" scale="100.00%" styleclass="T_Emphasis" figurelistinclude="0"></image><text styleclass="HowTo Bulleted" translate="true"> - the segment that has a different color.</text></li>
            <li styleclass="HowTo Bulleted"><text styleclass="Element" translate="true">Previous-Segment</text><text styleclass="HowTo Bulleted" translate="true"> - the segment before (to the left) the </text><text styleclass="Element" translate="true">Selected-Segment</text><text styleclass="HowTo Bulleted" translate="true">.</text></li>
            <li styleclass="HowTo Bulleted"><text styleclass="Element" translate="true">Next-Segment</text><text styleclass="HowTo Bulleted" translate="true"> - the segment after (to the right) the </text><text styleclass="Element" translate="true">Selected-Segment</text><text styleclass="HowTo Bulleted" translate="true">.</text></li>
          </list>
          <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">As soon as you click a different segment, it becomes the </text><text styleclass="VariableName" style="color:#ff0000;" translate="true">RED</text><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true"> </text><text styleclass="Element" translate="true">Selected-Segment</text><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" style="font-style:italic;" translate="true">. </text></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
  </body>
